data_answer: Dr. Gordon is emphasizing the intricacy and vastness of genomes. Individuals are not the expression of a single gene. Instead individuals are the expression of genes of different species working together. In his article, "Germs Are Us," Michael Specter states that genes have been looked upon as our "biological destiny [...] When DNA is damaged or genes interact poorly with one another the eventual result is disease" (Germs Are Us). Specter indicates the role that genomes play in an individual's body. Genes determine the structure of a person and DNA works together in order to help the individual live healthily. Inadequate interaction between DNA may result in diseases. Furthermore Dr. Gordon's quote conveys the vastness of genomes in our universe. Dr. Ruebush, author of, "Why Dirt is Good," demonstrates this vastness by writing, "The typical human probably harbors some 90 trillion microbes [...] The very fact that you have so many microbes of so many different kinds is what keeps you healthy most of the time" (Wash In Moderation).

data_answer: When source 2 says that "We are not just the expression of an individual human genome. We are, as Dr. Gordon writes, 'a genetic landscape,' a collective of genomes of hundreds of different species all working together," it is saying that if it weren't for germs we might not be alive. In source 1, it states that "bacteria are everywhere: on us, in us and all around us... and many, like the ones that normally live in the digestive tract and produce life-sustaining nutrients, are essential to good health." If something is essential to good health, then without it, good health is not achieved. It is said that it is because of these bacteria that our good health status is allowed to be. As such, ridding ourselves of these germs is not in our best interest. As such, we should keep them, or face the consequences. In the fifth source, it is said that "bacteria can battle numerous kinds of allergies-and not just food allergies." Allergies are usually very varied, ranging from coughing and sneezing to life-threatining situations. As such, anything that can combat allergies has the potential to remove a person from one of these life-threatening situations. By relation, taking away these bacteria, that can remove someone from the threat of death, means that that person is taking the risk of death simply by not taking the option to remove it. Therefore, it is blatantly obvious that bacteria are indeed useful, because they can save a life.

data_answer: Despite our insistence on the individuality of the human race, each man, woman, and child is not, so to speak, an "individual" according to source 2. All the cells that make up a human, are in close contact with nearly ten times as many foreign, non-human, microbes. As also stated in source 3, the characteristics we develop as we grow from infants into adults, are heavily influenced by the role off bacteria and viruses. In addition to the genetic differences caused by the patterning of DNA, the differences and similarities exhibited among the human population in the population of microbes in the body creates a sort of parallel evolutionary linneage. So in a way, we are two separate and combined families, each passing on our shared heritage to the next generation.

data_answer: Dr. Gordon expresses that we are much more than "an individual human genome" and that we are "a genetic landscape." We are defined by the actions we do and the people we affect, which is much similar to the "community" of bacteria and viruses that call our bodies home. Our bodies are like an "ecosystem" in which all the organisms in our body live "collaboratively" and "benignly" in order to create a functioning and healthy body. Germs are meant to be a part of our daily lives because our exposure to them allows our immune system to become stronger and be able to recognize diseases that will not potentially harm us. (Source #1) If we do not get enough exposure to these organisms found in the environment then we suffer with the consequences. Underdeveloped cities have the upperhand versus developed places because they are less affected by autoimmune diseases. Same goes for children raised on farms versus children in the city (Source #1). It is vital that we have these organisms working together in our bodies and when we are deficient we can nourish ourselves with foods or products targeted at bettering our immune systems like vitamins and yogurt (Source #4).

data_answer: What Dr. Gordon is trying to say is is that humans are not just humans. Humans are literally a landscape that is covered in a variety of microorganisms. These germs and bacteria that live on us and help us to function are needed in our lives. Without them, our bodies would have a struggle to protect themselves from harm. This is supported by source number one in the section labeled, "Training the Immune System." In this section, it states the fact that everyone knows, how all children tend to put almost everything they can into their mouths. It also states how this action is not necessarily a bad thing. When children do this, the immune responses can 'practice' and learn what is and what isn't good to digest and have. This stage in a human's life is essential, for again, it teaches their body and what lives on it what is best to be ignored and what is best to be taken in and used. Another source that supports this quote from "A Universe of Us" is, source number three. In this magazine, the writer has a paragraph that has this quote, "...By the time a child can crawl, he has been blanketed by an enormous, unseen cloud of microorganisms...a hundred trillion or more. They are bacteria...They congragate in our digestive systems and our mouths, fill the space between our teeth, cover our skin, and line our thoats... Together, they are reerred to as our microbiome - and they play such a crucial role in our lives..." This quote is perfect in explaining Dr. Gordon's idea. Humans are covered completely in other microorganisms like germs and bacteria. They live in us and on us. We are around them everyday and every second of each day. Germs are us. Without them we would not function correctly and be immuned to viruses and illnesses like the Chicken Pox. We should be thankful for having hundreds of different species on our genetic landscape. I know I sure am.

However, once the space crusades resulted in the destruction of the Eropoiqy, the galactic rulers of the galaxy and time, Columbus saw a chance to pursue his quest. He put on his helmet and flew his ship, and the rats hidden away in it, to the moon. Upon arrival, he ate some of the moon cheese due his glutoney. He then made the realization after eating said cheese that the moon was, in fact, a perfect sphere. A perfect sphere, besides the chunk of cheese he had taken from its surface. After coming to this realization, Columbus was forced to conclude that the moon was not round because of the cheese crater he had created. Following the announcent of his discovery, controversy raged as opponents of his ideas criticized his results, arguing that such a small chunk missing from the surface of the moon did not mean that the moon was not round. To settle the debate, Columbus challenged any who dared to a game of bingo; the winner of which would decide whether the moon was round or not. When none other of his opponents volunteered, Andrew Jackson accepted the challenge with honor, nobility, and a trick up his sleeve. He showed up to the match with a fixed bingo card, winning almost immediatly. On that same day, Jackson announced that the moon was round and merry times were had by all, except for Columbus. To escape the heartache, Columbus fled westward to seek solitude in India. Because of Jacksons heroics, it becomes clear that "We are not just the expression of an individual human genome. From source #3, "Germs make us sick," he said. "But everyone focuses on the harm. And it's not that simple, because without most of these organisms, we could never survive." data_answer: The passage fromt this article clarifies that humans are not just made up of human cells with human functions and DNA. Instead, there are trillions of bacterial and viral species that allow many human functions to take place. "Scientists now have discovered another realm within our habitat -- the virome, a large community of viruses. These are not the viruses that make us sick. These are an integral part of the microbiotic universe that make us healthy." Many of our necessary bodily functions would not be possible without this large community of viruses that the article "A Universe of Us" discusses. In addition, the strong, healthy immune systems we all strive to create would not be possible without this virome to fight back. According to Martin J. Blaser, professor of microbiology at the NYU School of Medicine, "germs make us sick, but everyone focuses on the harm. And it's not that simple, because without most of these organisms we would never survive." Blaser validates Gordon's argument by stating that it is necessary to locate the balance between germs that make us sick and germs that fight them off. Therefore, it becomes imperative for humans to explore the world of germs by getting dirty, exposing their immune systems to the outside world, and allowing them to build defense against the germs which create disease.

data_answer: Deoxy riboneuclaic acid, or DNA, is made up of four different bases. These bases (G,A,T, and C) do not change for any one species, in fact every living thing is made up of that swirling double helix. In the article, from the New York Times, "A Universe Of Us" the writer states that "We are not just the expression of an individual human genome," and he's right. The human genome shares 2% of its code with bannas, 5% of its code with gerbils, 90% with gorrillas, and between I, the writer, and everyone else in the world, there is a 1% difference in our genetic code. We don't even realilze that bacteria that "spur the development of a healthy immune system," and the germs that "play such a crucial in our lives," (these quotes are from the articles "Babies Know: A Little Dirt is Good for You", and " Eat Your Germs" respectivly) share the same bases in their small genetic code as we do ours. We are so connected, not even by the relationships and ecosystems we live in but even more closely by the DNA and genetic make up's we share.
